name: R/peak_fitting_FM.R
content:
library(stats)
library(tidyr)
#library(graphics)
library(ggplot2)


#### Enter number of peaks to fit 
fit_peaks <- function(spectrum_data,
                      positions, 
                      bkgd_limit,
                      begin_range, 
                      end_range,
                      tail_type='None',
                      fit_hydride_peaks=TRUE,
                      n_iter,
                      which_main_peak=NA,
                      plot_progress=FALSE){
  
  n_peaks = length(positions)
  
  peak_object <- list()
  peak_object$spectrum_data <- spectrum_data
  peak_object$begin_range <- begin_range
  peak_object$end_range <- end_range
  peak_object$bkgd_limit <- bkgd_limit
  peak_object$n_peaks <- n_peaks
  
  # Get spectra data and beginning and end ranges
  R <- spectrum_data[,2]
  R <- R[begin_range:end_range]
  time_of_flight = spectrum_data[begin_range:end_range,1]
  
  #### Subtract background, assumed to be a constant 
  bkgd_val <- mean(R[1:bkgd_limit])
  R <- R - bkgd_val # enter background estimate here for subtraction
  R[R < 0] <- 0 # all empirical spectrum values must non negative
  peak_object$R_sub_bkgd = R # need to be sure we save background-subtracted spectrum as well
  
  # Normalize
  max_channel <- max(R)
  peak_object$R_sub_bkgd = peak_object$R_sub_bkgd/max_channel
  R <- R/max_channel
  peak_object$R <- R
  
  

  
  ####  Calculate histogram bin width
  x <- spectrum_data[, 1]
  x <- x[begin_range:end_range]
  peak_object$x <- x
  
  bin_width <- x[2] - x[1]
  bin_width <- round(bin_width, 3)
  peak_object$bin_width <- bin_width
  
  n <- length(R)
  
  # sort positions in case they were entered out of order
  positions = sort(positions)
  
  # center positions at the max of the smoothed R near the user's selections
  res_cp = center_peaks(R,time_of_flight,positions)
  b_start = res_cp$b_start
  b_low = res_cp$b_low
  positions_index = res_cp$positions
  positions = time_of_flight[positions_index]
  
  # put leading peak index first in various vectors
  leading_peak_index = ifelse(is.na(which_main_peak),which.max(R[positions_index]),which_main_peak)
  swap_inds = c(leading_peak_index,(1:length(positions_index))[-leading_peak_index])
  positions_index = positions_index[swap_inds]
  positions = positions[swap_inds]
  b_low = b_low[swap_inds]
  b_start = b_start[swap_inds]
  
  
  # Create channel numbers matrix based off of peak position
  channel_numbers = create_channel_numbers(positions_index, n_peaks, n)
  
  # get constraints
  res_gci = get_constrained_inds(R=R,
                                 time_of_flight=time_of_flight,
                                 positions_index=positions_index,
                                 fit_hydride_peaks=fit_hydride_peaks)
  
  where_to_constrain = res_gci$where_to_constrain
  non_hydride_peaks = res_gci$non_hydride_peaks
  hydride_peaks = res_gci$hydride_peaks

  
  # fit reference spectrum 
  frs_res = fit_reference_spectrum(R=R,
                                   bkgd_limit=bkgd_limit,
                                   time_of_flight=time_of_flight,
                                   positions_index=positions_index)
    


  
  reference_spectrum = frs_res$rs

  res_et = estimate_tail(reference_spectrum,
                         R,
                         time_of_flight,
                         positions_index = positions_index,
                         bkgd_val,
                         method = tail_type)
  
  tail_limit = c((n_peaks + 1), res_et$tail_limit_guess)
  reference_spectrum = res_et$reference_spectrum
  
  p = reference_spectrum
  
  # define vector of parameters to optimize
  theta <- c(b_start, p)
  
  # default lower bound shouldn't be too much lower than ref spec
  low = c(b_low,(p*max_channel - 7*sqrt(p*max_channel))/max_channel )
  low[low < 0] = 0
  
  # upper bound should probably be pretty close to the reference spectrum
  # for the peak heights, need to use ratio of R to p, since tallest peak may not
  # be the reference peak
  up = c(2*rep(max(R)/max(p),n_peaks),(p*max_channel + 1*sqrt(p*max_channel))/max_channel)
  
  # constrain main peak to be 1 (other peaks can be higher or lower)
  up[1] = 1.01
  low[1] = .99
  
  # for hydride peaks, we need to track R, not the reference spectrum
  if(fit_hydride_peaks) {
    up[(n_peaks+1):length(up)][hydride_peaks] =  ((R*max_channel + 1*sqrt(R*max_channel))/max_channel)[hydride_peaks]
    low[(n_peaks+1):length(up)][hydride_peaks] =  ((R*max_channel - 1.5*sqrt(R*max_channel))/max_channel)[hydride_peaks]
  }
  
  # upper bound left of main peak should be the reference spectrum
  up[(n_peaks + 1):(n_peaks + positions_index[1])] = p[1:positions_index[1]]
  low[(n_peaks + 1):(n_peaks + positions_index[1])] = 0
  
  # fix constraints
  if(any(low > up)) {
    warning("Warning: Bounds are incorrect!")
  }
  
  if(plot_progress) {
    
    plot((R)^(1/4))
    lines((reference_spectrum)^(1/4),col='orange')
    lines((low[-(1:n_peaks)])^(1/4),col='red',lty=2)
    lines((up[-(1:n_peaks)])^(1/4),col='red',lty=2)
    lines(where_to_constrain-1)
    lines(hydride_peaks-.5,col='blue')
    abline(v=positions_index,col='blue')
    abline(v=positions_index[1],col='green')
    
  }
  
  
  new_theta = theta
  new_pos = positions_index
  new_channel = channel_numbers
  
  scaling_factors = rep(1,length(R)) # currently no scaling is really used
  
  f_values = rep(0,n_iter)

  ### begin optimization ###
  for(i in 1:n_iter){
    
    print(paste("Iteration:",i))
    
    print("fitting full spectrum...")
  
    # fit the peak shape and heights for fixed positions
    peaks <- optim(par = new_theta, fn = Q_theta, gr=gradient.eq,
                   method = 'L-BFGS-B', lower = low, upper = up,
                   R = R, n_peaks = n_peaks, n=n, channel_numbers=new_channel,
                   max_channel=max_channel,
                   scaling_factors = scaling_factors,
                   hessian=FALSE, control = list(maxit = 100, trace = TRUE,lmm=50))
    

    trial_points = -10:10
  
    # fit peak positions, greedy search
    curr_loss = Q_pos(new_pos,R,peaks,n_peaks,n,scaling_factors,max_channel)
    soln_pos = new_pos
    
    print("fitting positions..")
    
    for(ll in 1:length(positions_index)) {

      cand_pos = soln_pos
      t_cand_pos = soln_pos

      for(mm in trial_points) {

        t_cand_pos[ll] = cand_pos[ll] + round(mm)
        
        t_loss = Q_pos(t_cand_pos,R,peaks,n_peaks,n,scaling_factors,max_channel) 

        if(t_loss < curr_loss) {
          soln_pos[ll] = t_cand_pos[ll]
          curr_loss = t_loss
        }

      }

    }

    
    new_pos = soln_pos
    new_channel = create_channel_numbers(new_pos, n_peaks, n)
    new_theta = peaks$par
    
    f_values[i] = peaks$value
    
    if(i > 2) {
      if( sum(abs(diff(f_values[(i-2):i]))) < 10^(-8)) {
        print("Function values have not decreased for the last two iterations.")
        print("Terminating the optimization procedure.")
        break
      }
    }
    
  }
  
  # fit heights one last time
  
  if(!fit_hydride_peaks) {
    #plot(new_theta^(1/4))
    new_theta[n_peaks + new_pos[1]:length(R)] = Iso::pava(new_theta[n_peaks + new_pos[1]:length(R)],decreasing=T)
    #lines(new_theta^(1/4),col='red')
  }

  for(ii in 1:n_peaks) {
    
    t_res = optimize(f = Q_height,lower = low[ii],upper = up[ii],
                     height_index=ii,
                     theta=new_theta, 
                     R=R, 
                     n_peaks=n_peaks, 
                     n=n, 
                     channel_numbers=new_channel,
                     scaling_factors=scaling_factors,
                     max_channel=max_channel)
    
    new_theta[ii] = t_res$minimum
    
  }
  
  peaks[['new_channel']] <- new_channel
  peaks[['new_pos']] <- new_pos
  peaks$par = new_theta

  final_results <- peaks
  
  # Collecting calculations for final fit, also used in plotting
  fit_coefs <- final_results$par
  new_positions<-final_results$new_pos
  
  peak_shift <- vector(mode="numeric", length=n_peaks)
  d <- vector(mode="numeric", length=n_peaks)
  cvec <- vector(mode="numeric", length=n_peaks)
  
  for (i in 2:n_peaks){
    d[i]<-new_positions[i]-new_positions[1]
  }
  
  for (i in 2:n_peaks){
    cvec[i]<-(n-abs(d[i]))
  }
  
  spectra_results <- matrix(0, nrow=n_peaks, ncol=n)
  spectra_results[1, (1:n)] <- fit_coefs[(n_peaks + 1):(n + n_peaks)]
  
  for (i in 2:n_peaks){
    if (d[i]<=0){
      spectra_results[i, 1:cvec[i]] <- fit_coefs[i] * spectra_results[1, (abs(d[i]) + 1):(abs(d[i]) + cvec[i])]
    }else{
      spectra_results[i, (d[i] + 1): (d[i] + cvec[i])] <- fit_coefs[i] * spectra_results[1, 1:cvec[i]]
    }
  }
  
  total_fit <- colSums(spectra_results)
  final_resid <- R - total_fit
  
  
  peak_object$spectra_results <- spectra_results
  peak_object$total_fit <- total_fit
  peak_object$final_resid <- final_resid
  peak_object$nhp <- non_hydride_peaks
  peak_object$scaling_factors = scaling_factors
  peak_object$max_channel = max_channel
  
  final_results$peak_object <- peak_object
  class(final_results) <- "peak"
  
  return(final_results)
  
}

content:
This small Shiny application demonstrates Shiny's automatic UI updates. 

Move the *Number of bins* slider and notice how the `renderPlot` expression is automatically re-evaluated when its dependant, `input$bins`, changes, causing a histogram with a new number of bins to be rendered.
